###17 October 1925 De Pinedo Flight
On 21 April 1925 Major Francesco de Pinedo of the Italian Royal Air Force, accompanied by a mechanic, Ernesto Campanelli left Rome in a naval Savoia S16 hydroplane named _Gennariello_. He crossed southern Europe and Asia on his way to Sydney. Then he flew to Shanghai, skirting the East Indies, Philippines and Formosa. From Shanghai
he went via Korea to Kagoshima and then onto Tokyo. On his return trip he left Tokyo on 16 october, arriving in Shaghai on the 18th. Permission was obtained to carry mail for Hong Kong and Rome. This mail was posted at the nanking Post Office on the 17th and would have reached Shanghai the following morning in time for de pinedo's departure. However, on the day it was posted the troops at Chekiang Province cut the railway at several points in an attempt to cut off the retreat of those from Fengtien Province. Consequently, the mail had to be carried by steamer to 
Shanghai, which meant it arrived on the 20th. However, on the 19th, de Pinedo had to leave Shanghai without this mail, arriving back in Rome in his original plane, after a flight of 36,000 miles on, 8 November 1925.
