De Pinedo pioneered a number of other flights and was killed while taking off in a Bellanca monoplane on September 2, 1933, reportedly preparing to start a record length flight from New York City to Baghdad. One has to appreciate the risks these pioneers were taking and to respect these covers reminding us of these early days of long distance aviation. the tragic last flight was captured on film and you can view it at [Pinedo's Last Flight](http://youtu.be/9gpB9KLd9Bc).



###18 November 1928, Royal Air Force Far East Flight

The RAF Orient Flight, was made up of a squadron of four Southampton 'Supermarine' flying boats. The leader of the group was Captain Cave-Brown. They left Plymouth on 17 October 1927. Thei main purpose was to survey landing sites for the route to Autsralia. This mail carried the first official despatch for Hong Kong, which comprised covers from manila and Cabugao. To commemorate the arrival of this squadron in   Philippines stamps overprinted with a red flying boat and the initials "L.O.F." standing for "London Orient Flight" were issued. These commemoratives can be found used on the covers, which were cancelled Manila on 15 November and backstamped Hong Kong on the 18th on their arrival there. Covers were  carried at a minimum rate of 2 pesos.
